  "response_text": "**3-Day Meal Plan to Improve Iron Levels**\n\nAs a student, it's essential to maintain a balanced diet to support overall health and well-being. Iron deficiency is a common issue among students, particularly those with busy schedules or restrictive diets. This 3-day meal plan is designed to help improve iron levels, with a focus on iron-rich foods and vitamin C to enhance absorption.\n\n**Day 1**\n\n* **Breakfast**: Oatmeal with sliced banana, almond butter, and a splash of low-fat milk (1 cup cooked oatmeal: 3.5 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a glass of freshly squeezed orange juice (1 cup: 100% DV vitamin C) to enhance iron absorption\n* **Lunch**: Grilled chicken breast with roasted vegetables (bell peppers, zucchini, and onions) and quinoa (3 oz chicken breast: 1.5 mg iron, 1 cup cooked quinoa: 2.5 mg iron)\n\t+ Include a side of steamed spinach (1 cup: 4.9 mg iron) with a squeeze of lemon juice\n* **Dinner**: Baked salmon with sweet potato and green beans (3 oz salmon: 1.5 mg iron, 1 medium sweet potato: 1.7 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a side salad with mixed greens, cherry tomatoes, and a citrus vinaigrette dressing\n* **Snack**: Apple slices with peanut butter (1 medium apple: 0.5 mg iron, 2 tbsp peanut butter: 0.5 mg iron)\n\n**Day 2**\n\n* **Breakfast**: Scrambled eggs with whole wheat toast and sautéed mushrooms (2 eggs: 1.5 mg iron, 1 cup cooked mushrooms: 2.7 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a glass of freshly squeezed grapefruit juice (1 cup: 100% DV vitamin C) to enhance iron absorption\n* **Lunch**: Lentil soup with whole grain bread and a side of mixed berries (1 cup cooked lentils: 6.6 mg iron)\n\t+ Include a side salad with mixed greens, sliced avocado, and a lemon-tahini dressing\n* **Dinner**: Grilled turkey burger with roasted Brussels sprouts and brown rice (3 oz turkey burger: 2.5 mg iron, 1 cup cooked Brussels sprouts: 2.5 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a side of steamed asparagus with a squeeze of lemon juice\n* **Snack**: Dark chocolate square (1 oz: 3.5 mg iron) with a handful of dried apricots (1/4 cup: 1.5 mg iron)\n\n**Day 3**\n\n* **Breakfast**: Smoothie bowl with cooked spinach, frozen berries, banana, and almond milk topped with sliced almonds and shredded coconut (2 cups spinach: 9.8 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a splash of freshly squeezed orange juice to enhance iron absorption\n* **Lunch**: Grilled chicken wrap with mixed greens, sliced cucumber, and hummus (3 oz chicken breast: 1.5 mg iron, 2 tbsp hummus: 1.5 mg iron)\n\t+ Include a side of carrot sticks with a citrus-based dip\n* **Dinner**: Beef and vegetable stir-fry with brown rice (3 oz beef: 3.5 mg iron, 1 cup cooked broccoli: 2.5 mg iron)\n\t+ Add a side of steamed green beans with a squeeze of lemon juice\n* **Snack**: Rice cakes with almond butter and sliced banana (2 rice cakes: 1.5 mg iron, 2 tbsp almond butter: 1.5 mg iron)\n\n**Additional Tips**\n\n* Cook in cast-iron cookware to increase iron intake\n* Avoid consuming tea, coffee, or milk with meals, as they can inhibit iron absorption\n* Include a source of vitamin C (e.g., citrus fruits, bell peppers, or tomatoes) with each meal to enhance iron absorption\n* Consider taking an iron supplement after consulting with a healthcare professional or registered dietitian\n\nRemember, a well-balanced diet and a healthy lifestyle can help improve iron levels. This meal plan is designed to provide a general guideline, and individual iron needs may vary. Consult with a healthcare professional or registered dietitian for personalized recommendations.",
